node.text: We’ve been busy getting organized and ready to start documenting all of varieties in the dahlia breeding patch. Each “keeper” will get evaluated, written about, harvested, photographed and it’s very own variety sheet in our big breeding binders. There are currently 380 varieties to go through and we’re trying to be both very selective (only keeping the very best) and organized (checking all of the documentation boxes) so in the end we have tons of great information to work with. #discoveringdahlias

node.title: I thought I’d give you a little tour of the dahlia breeding patch!

node.text: I've been getting so many questions about the Floret books which we now refer to as the Floret library! I thought it would be fun to tell you a little bit more about each one. My first book, Cut Flower Garden, goes into all of the basics of planning a cutting garden, everything from starting seeds to caring for plants in the ground. Each chapter has important garden tasks and seasonal projects. Plus, it contains more than 175 of my favorite varieties for cutting. A Year in Flowers, our second book (which was a New York Times bestseller!), is all about arranging seasonal blooms. The front of the book demonstrates 7 essential flower arranging techniques with step-by-step instructions. These are the techniques I use all the time to make loose, natural looking arrangements. We then show each essential technique in spring, summer, autumn, and winter—it really is possible to arrange something beautiful every time of the year. The back of the book features harvesting and vase life tricks for more than 100 varieties so you can get the maximum enjoyment out of your flowers. This is the book I wish had existed when I first started out! Our third book, Discovering Dahlias, does a deep dive into one of my favorite flowers and tells you everything you need to know about these stars of summer in an easy to understand way. We include photo instructions for dividing and storing dahlia tubers and even have a section all about breeding your own dahlia varieties if you really want to get crazy. And we included more than 350 of my favorite varieties in the Variety Finder section of the book. My hope is that these books help you have success growing the garden of your dreams. #ayearinflowers #cutflowergarden #discoveringdahlias #floretbook

node.text: I thought it’d be fun to show you the Precious Metals Zinnias plus share my trick for knowing when to harvest these flowers. Zinnias need to be picked on the riper side and the easiest way to tell when they are ready is to use the “wiggle test”. If you haven’t joined our Summer Mini Course yet I’ve put a link in my bio (click the visit website button). It’s free to take and includes 3 helpful video tutorials including how to pinch your plants to get more flowers and longer stems, when and where to harvest for the longest vase life and how to make a mixed bouquet fast. Hope this helps! #floretworkshop #floretseeds

node.text: things that we encountered when making Discovering Dahlias was how to organize and display the incredible diversity found in this family of plants. Of all the colors that we explored in the book, yellow by far had the most variation by far. This one color category includes buttercream, lemon meringue, canary, goldenrod, honey, and highlighter yellow. In my experience, it seems like people either love yellow or totally hate it, and my hope is that this section of the book will bring people over to the brighter side. #discoveringdahlias

node.text: about the fact that we thought making this book was going to be easy. I think because we had so much experience, so many years already invested in documenting the flowers, and so much love for them that we naively assumed that it would be a slam dunk. But boy were we wrong! Thank goodness for @juliechai's level head, exceptional attention to detail, and incredible ability to manage such a complex project with grace. Without her guidance, we surely would have been lost. This book was the most challenging project we’ve taken on to date, but I think in the end, it is our most beautiful and comprehensive. As the books are leaving the farm and heading to your mailboxes all over the world, the four of us couldn’t be more excited for you to hold it in your hands. #discoveringdahlias

node.text: my very favorite place on the farm was the dahlia breeding patch. I spent so many evenings and weekends in this magical little spot combing the rows and discovering new treasures. One of the coolest parts about writing Discovering Dahlias was being able to include an entire chapter all about dahlia breeding, plus getting to highlight my dahlia breeding hero @santacruzdahlias. I am so excited to share what I’ve learned about breeding new varieties. It’s not actually as hard as you think, and you don’t need a lot of space to do it. I hope this chapter will inspire you to give it a try in the coming season! #discoveringdahlias

The book launches on March 9 and while we’re currently sold out of signed copies in the Floret Shop until launch day, there’s a great list of other sources to order from linked in my bio. Massive thanks to @robfinch for his expert guidance while we were putting this together. It so perfectly captures the essence of the book and what it was like making it for you all! #discoveringdahlias

node.text: creating some special dahlia-focused resources as a thank you for pre-ordering the Discovering Dahlias book. The wait is finally over, and I'm thrilled to finally be able to share them with you! When you pre-order Discovering Dahlias you'll receive: 1) A special two-part video series that takes you behind the scenes here at Floret. In the first video we'll take a tour of the Floret rainbow dahlia field, and I'll show you how to harvest and care for your freshly cut dahlias to ensure the longest vase life. In the second video we'll head into my flower studio and explore the incredible range of sizes, colors, and forms found in this amazing group of plants. 2) A set of printable planning cards featuring all 360 dahlias from the Variety Finder section of the book, plus over a dozen new additions that we've discovered and fallen in love with since the book went to print. These printable cards are what we use to plan our field and contain all the information you need to know: what the dahlia looks like, the variety name, flower color, flower type, and bloom size. 3) A comprehensive list of our favorite mail-order dahlia suppliers, including domestic and international sources for both common and hard-to-find varieties. This bonus is available with your pre-order of Discovering Dahlias, no matter where you get your copy from, or how long ago you preordered. To get the bonus gifts visit the book page on the Floret website (I put a link in my bio) to submit your receipt number. Scroll about 1/3 of the way down the page for the spot to enter your info. Upon receipt of your submission, we’ll send your bonus materials via email. If you pre-ordered your book through the Floret Shop it should have already been emailed to you and yes, you will still get a packet of dahlia seeds with your signed copy in March. I can’t wait for you to see these special thank you gifts!!! #discoveringdahlias

node.text: We’ve been busy getting organized and ready to start documenting all of varieties in the dahlia breeding patch. Each “keeper” will get evaluated, written about, harvested, photographed and it’s very own variety sheet in our big breeding binders. There are currently 380 varieties to go through and we’re trying to be both very selective (only keeping the very best) and organized (checking all of the documentation boxes) so in the end we have tons of great information to work with. #discoveringdahlias

I've been getting so many questions about the Floret books which we now refer to as the Floret library! I thought it would be fun to tell you a little bit more about each one. My first book, Cut Flower Garden, goes into all of the basics of planning a cutting garden, everything from starting seeds to caring for plants in the ground. Each chapter has important garden tasks and seasonal projects. Plus, it contains more than 175 of my favorite varieties for cutting. A Year in Flowers, our second book (which was a New York Times bestseller!), is all about arranging seasonal blooms. The front of the book demonstrates 7 essential flower arranging techniques with step-by-step instructions. These are the techniques I use all the time to make loose, natural looking arrangements. We then show each essential technique in spring, summer, autumn, and winter—it really is possible to arrange something beautiful every time of the year. The back of the book features harvesting and vase life tricks for more than 100 varieties so you can get the maximum enjoyment out of your flowers. This is the book I wish had existed when I first started out! Our third book, Discovering Dahlias, does a deep dive into one of my favorite flowers and tells you everything you need to know about these stars of summer in an easy to understand way. We include photo instructions for dividing and storing dahlia tubers and even have a section all about breeding your own dahlia varieties if you really want to get crazy. And we included more than 350 of my favorite varieties in the Variety Finder section of the book. My hope is that these books help you have success growing the garden of your dreams. #ayearinflowers #cutflowergarden #discoveringdahlias #floretbook

node.text: I thought it’d be fun to show you the Precious Metals Zinnias plus share my trick for knowing when to harvest these flowers. Zinnias need to be picked on the riper side and the easiest way to tell when they are ready is to use the “wiggle test”. If you haven’t joined our Summer Mini Course yet I’ve put a link in my bio (click the visit website button). It’s free to take and includes 3 helpful video tutorials including how to pinch your plants to get more flowers and longer stems, when and where to harvest for the longest vase life and how to make a mixed bouquet fast. Hope this helps! #floretworkshop #floretseeds

node.text: I’ve been a fan and a student of @marieforleo for nearly a decade now. She is one of the wisest, most generous, and most inspiring female entrepreneurs of our time. I can trace so much of our success back to what I learned from Marie—her work has truly changed my life. Last month I had the pleasure of sitting down with Marie (pictured here) to film a segment for her show. The experience was a full-circle moment for me because, after all these years of learning from her, I finally had something to share in return. We talked about so many meaningful things, including growing a business on your own terms, the importance of trusting your gut, and what it really takes to stay true to your heart and make it as an entrepreneur. I am so excited to finally be able to share our conversation with you. To watch the interview click the link in my bio. And the beautiful painting hanging in the background (you’ll see when you watch the interview) is by @morgan.allender 💕#growingfloret #bschool

node.text: With so many new followers I thought it would be a great time to introduce myself. I’m Erin and I run a flower farm and seed company called Floret with the help of my husband @copterchris (pictured here) and the amazing #teamfloret. Our farm is located in Washington's beautiful Skagit Valley, about an hour north of Seattle. I've been growing flowers professionally for more than 15 years now and love to share what I've learned along the way. You’ll find hundreds of photo-filled how-to’s, articles, and essays all about our farm and growing cut flowers over on my blog. My first book, Cut Flower Garden (all about growing flowers) came out in 2017 and my second book, A Year in Flowers (all about arranging seasonal blooms) was published in 2020. My third book, Discovering Dahlias (about one of my all-time favorite cut flowers) was released this March. In addition to offering a wide range of cut flower seeds through our online shop, I’m also a budding plant breeder and have been hard at work trying to create a range of easy-to-grow flowers (celosia, zinnias, and dahlias) that thrive in all climates (especially hot ones!) but come in a soft range of colors that growers, designers, and gardeners desperately want. Once a year I teach the Floret Online Workshop, an in-depth course focused on growing flowers on a small scale. And last but not least, Growing Floret, a documentary series about our farm, was just released on the new @magnolianetwork last week. I am so excited to have you along for this flower-filled ride! If you want to be the first to know about all of the amazing things we have coming up, be sure to join our newsletter list (link in bio). Photo courtesy of Magnolia Network, taken by @robfinch. #discoveringdahlias #ayearinflowers #growingfloret

node.text: Thank you for all of your enthusiasm about our show Growing Floret! The team and I have been reading and trying to respond to all of your emails, messages, and comments and I’m so happy that the show has resonated on such a deep level. So many of you have written to us sharing how many times you were in tears watching it which I think is a very good sign. What a gift to the world that @joannagaines @chipgaines vision for their @magnolianetwork is to tell real stories about real people taking big risks and going for their dreams. This series wouldn’t have been possible without @robfinch vision and the unwavering integrity of the @bluechalkmedia team and the years of hard work they all poured into this project. If you haven’t watched the show, you can visit the link in my bio to get all the details. Sadly the show is not currently available for international viewers but we hope this happens in the near future and I’ll be sure to share any updates as we go forward. node.text: More than two years ago we began the journey of filming a documentary series about our farm for the new @magnolianetwork. At the time, we didn’t know how the project would take shape or how the story would unfold and I remember being so nervous about all of the unknowns. In the end, I couldn’t be happier with how it turned out and am blown away by how honestly and beautifully @bluechalkmedia and @robfinch captured our story to share with the world. I’m so excited to share that all four episodes of Growing Floret are finally available today. For all the details about how to tune in, visit the link in my bio. The show is not currently available for international viewers but we hope this happens in the near future and I’ll be sure to share any updates I get as we go forward. node.text: It is a busy, busy blur right now. So many rows to walk, plants to check, hoops to rogue, photos to take, notes to write....I’m at the point in the season where I feel like I’m full on running to catch it. I have to remind myself that I always feel overwhelmed and behind in July. It doesn’t mean that anything is wrong, I just need to be ruthless when it comes to prioritizing my own projects and not get caught up in all of the other things pulling for my attention right now. This is a beautiful buff zinnia selection we’re working on that originated from @dawncreekfarm seeds. I’m so excited to see where it goes! 💫 #floretseeds

node.text: The first dahlia armload of the season! And what’s even more exciting is that these babies are all from my breeding patch. We have been running to get all of our zinnia and celosia breeding record keeping and photo documentation done knowing that dahlias are hot on their heels. I’m so excited to see what new varieties emerge this year and if the selections I made in years past are as good as I remember them to be. #discoveringdahlias #floretseeds

node.text: Walking the farm tonight and popped into one of my favorite breeding isolation hoops to see how things are going. This is a tufted selection of zinnias that originated in a mix of @dawncreekfarm seed that I grew out last year. There were a handful of tufted varieties in the mix which I saved seed from and then grew out separately this year. I’ve had to rogue (remove off types) the selection pretty hard but still have a few hundreds plants with crazy, fluffy, tufted centers and I’m in love with their wildness. Swipe through to see a few. Thank you to everyone who emailed in and sent enthusiastic/encouraging messages in response to today’s newsletter about our seed breeding program. I’m so happy you’re as excited about it as I am! #floretseeds
